 1193: /* Marker: inline SVG pin anchored at its tip (bottom-center). Using an SVG
 1194:  * rather than CSS clip-path guarantees visibility on every browser (mobile
 1195:  * Safari, older Android WebView, etc.) where `clip-path: path()` support
 1196:  * has been historically spotty. The transform origin at bottom-center
 1197:  * keeps the tip exactly on the converted point when we rescale in larger
 1198:  * map modes. */
 1199: /* ======  MARKER  ======
 1200:  * Stacking:  z-index 8 — above all tile-ctrls/overlays (z-index 6) so the
 1201:  * pin is never hidden by the scale, cursor or elevation pills, even when
 1202:  * the user has panned the view so the point lands near a corner.
 1203:  * Size:      36×52 px (scales up in half/full with transform:scale()).
 1204:  * Halo:      soft shadow ellipse under the tip.
 1205:  * Pulse:     expanding accent-yellow ring centered exactly on the tip to
 1206:  *            draw the eye immediately and make it obvious which pixel the
 1207:  *            MGRS string refers to. */
 1208: .tile-map .tile-marker{
 1209:   position:absolute;
 1210:   width:36px; height:52px;
 1211:   margin-left:-18px; margin-top:-52px;
 1212:   z-index:8; pointer-events:none;
 1213:   filter:drop-shadow(0 3px 5px rgba(0,0,0,.6));
 1214:   transform-origin:50% 100%;
 1215: }
 1216: .tile-map .tile-marker svg{display:block; width:100%; height:100%}
 1217: /* Soft ellipse of shade cast by the pin onto the tile, directly under the
 1218:  * tip. Improves grounding on very light imagery (snow, water, white roofs). */
 1219: .tile-map .tile-marker::before{
 1220:   content:""; position:absolute;
 1221:   left:50%; bottom:-6px;
 1222:   width:22px; height:8px; margin-left:-11px;
 1223:   background:rgba(0,0,0,.45); border-radius:50%;
 1224:   filter:blur(2px);
 1225:   z-index:-1;
 1226: }
 1227: /* Pulsing accent ring anchored at the exact pin tip (margin-bottom:-X makes
 1228:  * the ring center land on (0,0) of the .tile-marker container, i.e. on the
 1229:  * pin's 14,40 tip). It runs a slow radial pulse that draws attention to the
 1230:  * geodetic point without being visually noisy. */
